The Week of Impossible Dawns: a seven-day period when the Great Pyramid's containment of the Black Sun Shard partially failed.
Sunlight cast wrong shadows; stars were visible at noon; funerary wards ignited in empty streets.
The destabilization pulse propagated through the obelisk-line network, affecting every connected structure simultaneously.
In the Eastern Desert: charter stones bore unreadable inscriptions, oasis water turned brackish, travelers arrived at unintended destinations.
In the Northern Pyramid: guardian spirits attacked each other; the Sand Sovereign's spirit spoke in Seal College technical language it had never learned in life.
In the Southern Pyramid: tier wardens wept obsidian tears — liquid volcanic glass — and inscriptions recorded "the grief of those who knew first."
The Great Pyramid sealed itself via automatic protocols and bloodline locks with no living custodians available to oversee the process.
Surrounding settlements were abandoned in waves as containment uncertainty persisted past the seven-day event.
The Eclipsed Tongues faction was formally founded during this period, framing the event as theological confirmation of Moon Sovereign doctrine.
Outlying Jackal Tribunal officers, stranded without central command, devolved over generations into militant toll-priests — the modern Jackal Synod.
No single event before or since has affected as many distant locations simultaneously through a single propagation mechanism.
The Week established the current geographic distribution of anomalous ruins: locations where normal rules do not apply cluster around obelisk-line termini.
The obelisk-line network, designed to mark legal travel windows and ration days, had never been assessed as a potential resonance transmission system.

